- Come on!

485
00:48:16,687 --> 00:48:19,440
Try again. See if you can let
Captain Hamill know we're coming.

486
00:48:19,523 --> 00:48:22,109
What's the rest of Neuville look like?

487
00:48:22,192 --> 00:48:24,611
Next block's got two-story buildings,
both sides of the street.

488
00:48:24,695 --> 00:48:26,055
- There's a lot of windows.
- ...copy? Over.

489
00:48:26,155 --> 00:48:29,199
And then there's a wide open square
with pretty good cover on the left.

490
00:48:29,299 --> 00:48:31,118
- Show me.
- Sarge, hold right here.

491
00:48:31,201 --> 00:48:32,619
Yes, sir!

492
00:48:36,790 --> 00:48:39,573
All right. Let's stay out of this
enfilade and use the buildings.

493
00:48:39,673 --> 00:48:40,627
Try a left hook.

494
00:48:40,711 --> 00:48:42,588
Shoot and scoot,
two of yours, two of mine.

495
00:48:42,671 --> 00:48:45,132
Hastings, Goldman, up front!

496
00:48:46,175 --> 00:48:48,969
- Reiben, Caparzo. Fundamentals.
- They're still jamming us.

497
00:48:49,052 --> 00:48:51,638
Short runs. High and low at the corners.

498
00:48:51,722 --> 00:48:54,224
It's gonna be tight.
Be prepared for close contact.

499
00:48:54,308 --> 00:48:56,143
- Go. Upham.
- Yes, sir.

500
00:48:56,226 --> 00:48:58,444
- You stay with Sergeant Horvath.
- Stay right here.

501
00:48:58,544 --> 00:49:02,215
I'll wear him like underwear, Captain!
Stay with me.

502
00:49:10,199 --> 00:49:11,658
All right, past the end
of the block to the left.

503
00:49:11,742 --> 00:49:13,221
Those are the gates to the square.

504
00:49:13,321 --> 00:49:14,655
Good.

505
00:49:22,252 --> 00:49:24,004
Reiben, where's the captain from?

506
00:49:24,087 --> 00:49:26,435
You figure that one out,
you got yourself a nice prize.

507
00:49:26,535 --> 00:49:28,008
300 bucks, last I heard.

508
00:49:28,091 --> 00:49:31,345
Company's got a pool.
5 bucks gets you in.

509
00:49:35,766 --> 00:49:37,100
Easy.

510
00:49:38,685 --> 00:49:42,564
It's around this corner.
Defilade right up to those gates.

511
00:49:43,632 --> 00:49:46,135
Somebody must know where he's from,
what he did for a living.

512
00:49:46,235 --> 00:49:48,028
I've been with him
since Kasserine Pass,

513
00:49:48,111 --> 00:49:49,279
but I don't have a clue.

514
00:49:49,404 --> 00:49:51,198
My ankles are killing me.

515
00:49:51,281 --> 00:49:54,201
I'll need a wheelchair
before this war is over.

516
00:49:54,284 --> 00:49:56,787
Oh, that's it. Oh, my God.

517
00:49:56,870 --> 00:50:00,123
Got ankles like an old woman.
Like an old...

518
00:50:00,207 --> 00:50:01,917
Oh, God.

519
00:50:03,627 --> 00:50:06,797
Reiben, so, you don't even know
where he went to school?

520
00:50:06,913 --> 00:50:08,131
Captain didn't go to school.

521
00:50:08,215 --> 00:50:11,385
They assembled him at OCS
out of spare body parts of dead GIs.

522
00:50:11,468 --> 00:50:12,947
You gotta pay attention to detail.

523
00:50:13,072 --> 00:50:15,377
I know exactly where he's from
and exactly what he did

524
00:50:15,477 --> 00:50:17,140
'cause I pay attention to detail.

525
00:50:17,266 --> 00:50:20,727
Hey, Upham,
careful you don't step in the bullshit.

526
00:50:26,066 --> 00:50:28,402
- Do it.
- Thunder!

527
00:50:28,485 --> 00:50:31,655
Thunder, or we will fire on you!

528
00:50:40,998 --> 00:50:44,459
Upham, tell them to show themselves.

529
00:50:55,762 --> 00:50:58,807
Ask them if they know
where the Germans are.

530
00:51:02,936 --> 00:51:05,814
«- What's he saying?
- Something about the children.»

531
00:51:06,157 --> 00:51:09,359
- They want us to take the children.
- No, no, no. We can't take the kids.

532
00:51:09,443 --> 00:51:11,111
We can't take the kids. We can't!

533
00:51:11,194 --> 00:51:14,448
«We can't take the kids! No!»

534
00:51:17,326 --> 00:51:18,848
«They think they'll be safe with us.»

535
00:51:18,931 --> 00:51:21,100
«It's not gonna be
safe when they're with us!»

536
00:51:21,225 --> 00:51:24,175
- It's okay. It's okay.
- Are you nuts? Listen to the captain!

537
00:51:24,958 --> 00:51:26,627
Are you nuts? Listen to the captain!

538
00:51:26,710 --> 00:51:28,712
«They think they'll be safe with us, sir.»

539
00:51:29,046 --> 00:51:32,341
«Caparzo! Put that kid back!»

540
00:51:32,799 --> 00:51:34,051
It's okay.

541
00:51:34,176 --> 00:51:37,387
«- Caparzo! Put that little girl back!»
- It's okay. It's okay. It's okay.

542
00:51:37,512 --> 00:51:40,557
Caparzo, give that kid back now!

543
00:51:40,641 --> 00:51:42,225
Upham, how do you say, "It's okay"?

544
00:51:42,768 --> 00:51:44,645
I can't. She reminds me
of my niece, sir.

545
00:51:44,728 --> 00:51:46,730
Caparzo, get the kid back up there!

546
00:51:46,813 --> 00:51:48,248
Captain, the decent thing to do

547
00:51:48,331 --> 00:51:50,679
is to at least take her down
the road to the next town.

548
00:51:50,704 --> 00:51:53,922
We're not here to do the decent thing!
We're here to follow fucking orders!

549
00:51:54,041 --> 00:51:56,239
Sarge, take this goddamn kid!

550
00:51:56,990 --> 00:51:59,159
Cover! Cover!

551
00:52:08,418 --> 00:52:11,380
God damn it! Where'd that come from?

552
00:52:13,173 --> 00:52:16,593
He was on the ground
before we heard the shot.

553
00:52:21,390 --> 00:52:23,266
That's where I'd be.

554
00:52:25,185 --> 00:52:26,395
I didn't see it.

555
00:52:26,478 --> 00:52:29,314
Four hundred fifty yards, Captain.
Maybe a shade under.

556
00:52:29,398 --> 00:52:33,652
I wouldn't venture out there, fellas!
This sniper's got talent!

557
00:52:38,115 --> 00:52:41,576
Please don't cry. I'm gonna take you
back to your mama and papa.

558
00:52:41,660 --> 00:52:43,870
Please don't cry. Come on.

559
00:52:47,124 --> 00:52:48,542
Carpy.

560
00:52:59,636 --> 00:53:01,972
- Captain.
- Hold on, Caparzo.

561
00:53:03,390 --> 00:53:05,559
Help me up. I can walk. I can walk.

562
00:53:05,642 --> 00:53:07,811
Caparzo, stay still!

563
00:53:19,239 --> 00:53:21,533
Two clicks, left wind.

564
00:53:25,203 --> 00:53:26,538
Fish!

565
00:53:34,504 --> 00:53:37,340
Captain, can you see him
from there? How is he?

566
00:53:37,424 --> 00:53:39,384
Wade, you stay put.

567
00:53:39,509 --> 00:53:41,678
Where's he shot, Captain?

568
00:53:43,513 --> 00:53:46,057
- Captain, can you see him from there?
- You stay there!

569
00:53:46,183 --> 00:53:49,811
Damn it, stay down!
What's the matter with you?

570
00:53:49,895 --> 00:53:53,648
Am I gonna take care of you
if you get hit? Huh?

571
00:53:53,732 --> 00:53:56,985
- Fish, come over here.
- Carpy, put your head down.

572
00:53:57,068 --> 00:54:00,238
Why can't you put your head down?

573
00:54:07,871 --> 00:54:10,749
O my God, I trust in thee.

574
00:54:10,874 --> 00:54:12,876
Let me not be ashamed.

575
00:54:13,710 --> 00:54:16,546
Let not my enemies triumph over me.

576
00:54:26,389 --> 00:54:28,058
Copy it.

577
00:54:28,141 --> 00:54:30,477
Copy it and send it for me.

578
00:54:30,560 --> 00:54:33,021
Carpy, you're gonna send it yourself.
Put it down!

579
00:54:33,104 --> 00:54:36,399
- It's got blood!
- I see it. Carpy, I see it.

580
00:54:40,946 --> 00:54:45,075
It's to my dad.
It's got blood on it, Fish.

581
00:55:13,103 --> 00:55:15,647
We got him. Stay down.

582
00:55:24,364 --> 00:55:28,577
- How bad is it?
- Chest, maybe lung shot.

583
00:55:44,009 --> 00:55:46,553
Get that 30 up the street!

584
00:55:51,349 --> 00:55:52,601
«Detail!»

585
00:55:52,684 --> 00:55:54,769
«- Clear up!
- Clear down!»

586
00:56:10,410 --> 00:56:13,330
That's why we can't take children.

587
00:56:19,377 --> 00:56:22,964
Sergeant Horvath, do an ammo check.

588
00:56:23,048 --> 00:56:26,718
Upham, canteens. Fill them up.

589
00:56:27,302 --> 00:56:29,095
«- Sergeant Hill.
- Yes, sir.»

590
00:56:29,179 --> 00:56:33,558
«Gather your men. We'll form up
at the northwest corner of the square.»

591
00:56:33,642 --> 00:56:35,310
«- Jackson!
- Sir.»

592
00:56:35,393 --> 00:56:40,190
«Mellish, check the tower,
hustle back here. Right now. Go!»

593
00:56:52,035 --> 00:56:53,662
Fuck Ryan.

594
00:57:04,172 --> 00:57:06,591
- Thunder!
«- Flash!»

595
00:57:06,675 --> 00:57:08,218
«Come on in.»

596
00:57:13,014 --> 00:57:15,266
Hey, guys, we're looking
for Captain Hamill.

597
00:57:15,350 --> 00:57:17,102
Somewhere down there
across the square.

598
00:57:17,185 --> 00:57:18,478
Across the square.

599
00:57:18,561 --> 00:57:21,147
Go easy. Watch for snipers.

600
00:57:21,731 --> 00:57:23,483
«Sit down.»

601
00:57:40,041 --> 00:57:42,627
Jimmy T, go find Captain Hamill,
bring him in here.

602
00:57:42,711 --> 00:57:44,045
What? Up there?

603
00:57:44,129 --> 00:57:46,881
How the hell should I know?
Would you go look, please?

604
00:57:46,965 --> 00:57:48,925
Thank you, you moron.

605
00:57:50,301 --> 00:57:51,886
All right.

606
00:57:51,970 --> 00:57:55,432
You guys just flake out
here for a while.

607
00:57:57,392 --> 00:58:00,854
Let me get this goddamn
hitchhiker out of my boot.

608
00:58:10,822 --> 00:58:12,615
Drop your weapons!
Drop your weapons!

609
00:58:12,741 --> 00:58:15,952
- Drop them now!
- Drop the fucking weapons!

610
00:58:18,788 --> 00:58:22,834
- I'll shoot you! I'll shoot you!
- Drop! Drop! Drop them!

611
00:58:25,336 --> 00:58:27,630
Now! Put them down!

612
00:58:42,771 --> 00:58:44,189
Clear up!

613
00:58:49,486 --> 00:58:53,156
- Shit. Shit!
«- Clear up!»

614
00:58:54,657 --> 00:58:56,201
Clear down!

615
00:59:08,171 --> 00:59:11,925
- Enough to make you old.
- Let's hope so.

616
00:59:22,852 --> 00:59:24,395
Fred Hamill, Pathfinders, 101st.

617
00:59:24,479 --> 00:59:27,440
John Miller, 2nd Rangers. Thank you.

618
00:59:29,359 --> 00:59:31,229
We're here looking
for a Private James Ryan.

619
00:59:31,329 --> 00:59:34,332
He's part of your outfit.
Any chance at all you policed him up?

620
00:59:34,781 --> 00:59:37,325
- How was the road in?
- Scenic.

621
00:59:37,867 --> 00:59:41,579
- We lost most of our ammo.
- Not to mention one of our men.

622
00:59:42,080 --> 00:59:45,333
Lieutenant, redeploy that bazooka
to the right side of the road.

623
00:59:45,583 --> 00:59:48,378
«- Yes, sir!»
- And get Ryan up here.

624
00:59:50,713 --> 00:59:53,633
«Ryan! Ryan, front and center!»

625
00:59:54,134 --> 00:59:55,426
Ryan!

626
00:59:59,055 --> 01:00:01,099
Here comes our boy.

627
01:00:08,898 --> 01:00:11,568
Told you he was an asshole.

628
01:00:12,902 --> 01:00:15,238
- Sir, Private Ryan reporting as ordered.
- At ease.

629
01:00:15,738 --> 01:00:19,159
Captain Miller, 2nd Rangers.
He wants a word with you.

630
01:00:20,743 --> 01:00:22,245
This way.

631
01:00:23,121 --> 01:00:25,915
All right. Take a knee.

632
01:00:35,466 --> 01:00:38,803
Private, I'm afraid
I have some bad news for you.

633
01:00:46,477 --> 01:00:50,190
Well, there isn't any real
easy way to say this, so...

634
01:00:52,567 --> 01:00:55,778
So I'll just say it.
Your brothers are dead.

635
01:00:57,238 --> 01:01:00,950
We have orders to come get you

636
01:01:01,951 --> 01:01:04,120
because you're going home.

637
01:01:18,092 --> 01:01:20,720
Oh, my God. My brothers are dead.

638
01:01:28,144 --> 01:01:31,814
I was supposed to take them fishing
when we got home.

639
01:01:45,495 --> 01:01:48,706
I'm so sorry, James.
I can't tell you how much.

640
01:01:49,999 --> 01:01:54,379
- How... How did they die?
- They were killed in action.

641
01:01:56,881 --> 01:01:59,801
That can't be. They're...

642
01:02:00,510 --> 01:02:04,514
That... That can't be.
My brothers are still in grammar school.

643
01:02:07,892 --> 01:02:10,853
- You're James Ryan?
- Yeah.

644
01:02:11,980 --> 01:02:14,732
James Francis Ryan from Iowa?

645
01:02:15,233 --> 01:02:17,777
James Frederick Ryan, Minnesota.

646
01:02:24,701 --> 01:02:26,953
What? Does that mean
my brothers are okay?

647
01:02:27,036 --> 01:02:28,746
Yeah, I'm sure they're fine.

648
01:02:28,830 --> 01:02:30,623
Are you sure they're okay, though?

649
01:02:30,707 --> 01:02:32,534
We're looking
for a different Private Ryan.

650
01:02:32,634 --> 01:02:34,210
This is just a big foul-up.

651
01:02:34,294 --> 01:02:36,170
How do you know?
How can you be sure?

652
01:02:36,254 --> 01:02:40,383
How do you know the foul-up isn't
that his brothers are okay and that...

653
01:02:40,466 --> 01:02:42,635
Lieutenant, I'm sorry for the trouble.

654
01:02:42,719 --> 01:02:45,538
I just wrote them a letter
right before I left.

655
01:02:45,639 --> 01:02:46,989
«I got to get home.»

656
01:02:48,182 --> 01:02:50,143
«I got to get home right now.»

657
01:02:50,226 --> 01:02:52,729
«- I wanna go home.
- Easy, now.»

658
01:02:53,646 --> 01:02:55,864
- So, where in the hell is our Ryan?
- I don't know.

659
01:02:55,964 --> 01:02:57,317
Are you in touch with your CO?

660
01:02:57,400 --> 01:02:59,319
- That figures.
- What unit's your Ryan in?

661
01:02:59,402 --> 01:03:01,612
Baker Company, 506th.

662
01:03:01,696 --> 01:03:03,653
The guy with the broken foot,
he's 506, right?

663
01:03:03,753 --> 01:03:04,991
Yeah. Charlie, I think.

664
01:03:05,074 --> 01:03:06,743
- You think?
- Yeah.

665
01:03:06,826 --> 01:03:10,079
Ryan? Don't know... Man!

666
01:03:10,163 --> 01:03:12,749
«- Where was your drop zone?»
- Just inside of Vierville.

667
01:03:12,832 --> 01:03:15,710
«Vierville? How the hell did you
end up way up here?»

668
01:03:15,793 --> 01:03:19,005
You got me, sir. C-47 took heavy fire.

669
01:03:19,088 --> 01:03:22,045
Pilot went crazy trying to get out
of there, turning every which way.

670
01:03:22,145 --> 01:03:25,928
Took more fire on the drop.
Got messy. I ended up here.

671
01:03:26,012 --> 01:03:28,056
I haven't seen a single guy
from my stick, sir.

672
01:03:28,139 --> 01:03:29,557
God knows where they are.

673
01:03:29,640 --> 01:03:31,351
Anybody from Baker Company
have, like, a big mouth?

674
01:03:31,434 --> 01:03:33,348
Talk about where the drop zone
might've been?

675
01:03:33,448 --> 01:03:36,814
No, sir, but I know Baker Company
had the same rally point as us.

676
01:03:36,898 --> 01:03:38,149
Show me.

677
01:03:39,484 --> 01:03:40,526
My men are beat.

678
01:03:40,610 --> 01:03:42,862
We're gonna hold up here
for about three hours.

679
01:03:42,945 --> 01:03:44,322
We'll pull out after dark.

680
01:03:45,490 --> 01:03:48,368
Got anything left in this town
like a three-star hotel?

681
01:03:48,451 --> 01:03:51,746
Something with clean sheets
and soft pillows and room service?

682
01:03:51,829 --> 01:03:55,041
- How about a nice, comfy church?
- We'll take that.

683
01:03:55,124 --> 01:03:58,002
What have you heard?
How's it all falling together?

684
01:03:58,086 --> 01:03:59,712
Well, we got the beachhead secure.

685
01:03:59,796 --> 01:04:02,382
Problem is Monty's taking
his time moving on Caen.

686
01:04:02,465 --> 01:04:04,759
We can't pull out till he's ready, so...

687
01:04:04,842 --> 01:04:07,470
- That guy's overrated.
- No argument here.

688
01:04:07,553 --> 01:04:10,348
You gotta take Caen,
so you can take Saint-Lô.

689
01:04:10,431 --> 01:04:12,350
You got to take Saint-Lô
to take Valognes.

690
01:04:12,433 --> 01:04:14,102
Valognes, you got Cherbourg.

691
01:04:14,185 --> 01:04:17,522
- Cherbourg, you got Paris.
- Paris, you get Berlin.

692
01:04:17,980 --> 01:04:20,316
And then that big boat home.

693
01:04:23,694 --> 01:04:25,477
We sure as hell
could use you around here,

694
01:04:25,577 --> 01:04:27,532
but I understand what you're doing.

695
01:04:27,615 --> 01:04:29,242
- You do?
- Yeah.

696
01:04:29,325 --> 01:04:31,953
I got a couple of brothers myself.

697
01:04:32,495 --> 01:04:34,997
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

698
01:04:35,373 --> 01:04:39,335
No, I mean it. Find him. Get him home.

699
01:04:47,802 --> 01:04:49,804
«What's with your hand?»

700
01:04:51,264 --> 01:04:53,099
I don't know.

701
01:04:54,809 --> 01:04:56,102
It started in Portsmouth

702
01:04:56,185 --> 01:04:57,968
when they brought us
down for embarkation.

703
01:04:58,068 --> 01:04:59,480
It comes and goes.

704
01:04:59,564 --> 01:05:02,442
Well, you may have to get
yourself a new line of work.

705
01:05:02,525 --> 01:05:05,945
«This one doesn't seem
to agree with you anymore.»

706
01:05:11,200 --> 01:05:12,535
«What?»

707
01:05:17,206 --> 01:05:18,791
«- What?»
- Nothing.

708
01:05:19,542 --> 01:05:22,336
What was the name
of that kid at Anzio?

709
01:05:22,420 --> 01:05:25,073
The one that was always walking
around on his hands, you know?

710
01:05:25,173 --> 01:05:28,634
«And he was singing that song
about the man on the flying trapeze.»

711
01:05:28,718 --> 01:05:30,428
- Vecchio.
- Vecchio.

712
01:05:37,018 --> 01:05:38,352
«Yeah, Vecchio.»

713
01:05:38,436 --> 01:05:40,313
He was a goofy kid.

714
01:05:42,064 --> 01:05:45,067
Remember, he used to pee
a "V" on everybody's jacket

715
01:05:45,151 --> 01:05:48,404
for Vecchio, for victory.

716
01:05:53,075 --> 01:05:56,829
«He was so short.
He was a midget, wasn't he?»

717
01:05:56,913 --> 01:05:59,665
«How did you get to be a Ranger?»

718
01:06:00,917 --> 01:06:04,091
«He got shot in the foot once, didn't he,
when he was walking on his hands?»

719
01:06:04,191 --> 01:06:07,152
«Yeah. He could walk faster on his hands.»

720
01:06:07,423 --> 01:06:10,468
«He could run faster on his hands than...»

721
01:06:13,387 --> 01:06:14,764
Vecchio.

722
01:06:15,890 --> 01:06:17,141
Yeah.

723
01:06:18,768 --> 01:06:20,144
Caparzo.

724
01:06:26,651 --> 01:06:31,572
You see, when you end up
killing one of your men,

725
01:06:32,448 --> 01:06:35,576
you tell yourself it happened

726
01:06:35,660 --> 01:06:41,290
so you could save the lives
of two or three or 10 others.

727
01:06:42,959 --> 01:06:44,961
Maybe 100 others.

728
01:06:49,215 --> 01:06:52,176
Do you know how many men
I've lost under my command?

729
01:06:52,260 --> 01:06:54,470
«- How many?»
- Ninety-four.

730
01:06:55,888 --> 01:07:01,644
«But that means I've saved the lives
of 10 times that many, doesn't it?»

731
01:07:02,645 --> 01:07:06,065
Maybe even 20, right?
Twenty times as many?

732
01:07:12,154 --> 01:07:14,490
And that's how simple it is.

733
01:07:15,449 --> 01:07:17,159
That's how you...

734
01:07:18,494 --> 01:07:21,163
That's how you rationalize
making the choice

735
01:07:21,247 --> 01:07:23,749
«between the mission and the men.»

736
01:07:24,166 --> 01:07:27,295
Except this time, the mission is a man.

737
01:07:30,590 --> 01:07:33,050
This Ryan better be worth it.

738
01:07:36,053 --> 01:07:38,848
He'd better go home,
cure some disease,

739
01:07:38,931 --> 01:07:42,435
or invent a longer-lasting
light bulb or something.

740
01:07:43,227 --> 01:07:45,141
'Cause the truth is
I wouldn't trade 10 Ryans

741
01:07:45,241 --> 01:07:47,815
for one Vecchio or one Caparzo.

742
01:07:47,898 --> 01:07:49,191
Amen.

743
01:07:51,611 --> 01:07:53,738
Look. There it goes again.

744
01:07:54,780 --> 01:07:57,700
Sir, are you all right?

745
01:08:02,997 --> 01:08:06,292
Now, look, we're gonna
move out in two hours.

746
01:08:06,375 --> 01:08:08,628
Why don't you get some sleep?

747
01:08:08,711 --> 01:08:11,797
«- I don't know how he does it.
- What's that?»

748
01:08:11,881 --> 01:08:14,550
Falls asleep like that.
I mean, look at him.

749
01:08:14,634 --> 01:08:17,678
The guy's lights out the minute
his head hits the pack.

750
01:08:17,762 --> 01:08:19,347
Clear conscience.

751
01:08:19,430 --> 01:08:21,015
Yeah. What's that saying?

752
01:08:21,098 --> 01:08:24,268
"If God's on our side,
who the hell could be on theirs?"

753
01:08:24,352 --> 01:08:26,937
"If God be for us,
who could be against us?"

754
01:08:27,021 --> 01:08:29,148
«Yeah, what did I say?»

755
01:08:29,231 --> 01:08:33,486
«Well, actually, the trick
to falling asleep is trying to stay awake.»

756
01:08:33,569 --> 01:08:35,321
«How is that, Wade?»

757
01:08:35,404 --> 01:08:40,409
«Well, when my mother was an intern,
she used to work late through the night,»

758
01:08:40,493 --> 01:08:42,995
«sleep through the day.»

759
01:08:43,079 --> 01:08:44,955
So the only time that we ever got
to talk about anything

760
01:08:45,039 --> 01:08:46,499
was when she'd get home.

761
01:08:46,582 --> 01:08:49,126
So what I used to do,
I used to lie in my bed

762
01:08:49,210 --> 01:08:50,950
and try to stay awake
as long as I could,

763
01:08:51,050 --> 01:08:54,507
but it never worked
'cause the harder I tried,

764
01:08:54,590 --> 01:08:56,842
the faster I'd fall asleep.

765
01:08:57,619 --> 01:09:00,054
«Yeah. Well, that wouldn't have
mattered none in my house.»

766
01:09:00,137 --> 01:09:02,431
My ma, she would've come home,
shook me awake,

767
01:09:02,515 --> 01:09:04,350
chatted me up till dawn.

768
01:09:04,767 --> 01:09:06,977
I swear, that woman
was never too tired to talk.

769
01:09:07,061 --> 01:09:11,065
Yeah. That's probably the only time
she could get a word in.

770
01:09:15,111 --> 01:09:18,656
Funny thing is,
sometimes she'd come home early,

771
01:09:18,739 --> 01:09:21,367
and I'd pretend to be asleep.

772
01:09:21,450 --> 01:09:25,121
«- Who? Your mum?»
- Yeah.

773
01:09:27,790 --> 01:09:30,793
She'd stand in the doorway,
looking at me.

774
01:09:31,293 --> 01:09:33,713
And I'd just keep my eyes shut.

775
01:09:36,465 --> 01:09:40,094
And I knew she just wanted
to find out about my day,

776
01:09:40,678 --> 01:09:43,139
that she came home early

777
01:09:44,557 --> 01:09:46,517
just to talk to me.

778
01:09:49,729 --> 01:09:53,941
And I still wouldn't move.
I'd still pretend to just be asleep.

779
01:10:01,157 --> 01:10:03,451
I don't know why I did that.

780
01:10:17,006 --> 01:10:20,593
We only got a couple of hours.
Shut up and go to sleep.

781
01:10:29,351 --> 01:10:32,229
«Captain? Sir?»

782
01:10:34,273 --> 01:10:35,691
Corporal?

783
01:10:40,946 --> 01:10:44,033
How you doing there? Are you all right?

784
01:10:44,200 --> 01:10:47,203
Yeah, I think this is
all good for me, sir.

785
01:10:48,621 --> 01:10:50,080
Really?

786
01:10:50,831 --> 01:10:52,333
How is that?

787
01:10:56,253 --> 01:10:58,798
"War educates the senses,"

788
01:10:58,881 --> 01:11:00,841
"calls into action the will,"

789
01:11:00,925 --> 01:11:03,636
"perfects the physical constitution,"

790
01:11:04,011 --> 01:11:06,889
"brings men into such swift
and close collision"

791
01:11:06,972 --> 01:11:10,100
"in critical moments
that man measures man."

792
01:11:10,559 --> 01:11:13,270
Yeah. Well, I guess
that's Emerson's way

793
01:11:13,729 --> 01:11:15,481
of finding the bright side.

794
01:11:15,564 --> 01:11:19,235
- You know Emerson, sir?
- I know some.

795
01:11:23,739 --> 01:11:27,743
So, where are you from, Captain?
What'd you do before the war?

796
01:11:29,787 --> 01:11:32,122
What's the pool up to?

797
01:11:35,459 --> 01:11:38,295
You know, I think it's around 300, sir.

798
01:11:39,129 --> 01:11:41,799
Well, when it gets up to 500,

799
01:11:41,882 --> 01:11:44,143
I'll give you the answers,
and we'll split the money.

800
01:11:44,243 --> 01:11:46,220
How about that?

801
01:11:46,303 --> 01:11:49,890
Well, if that's the way you feel, sir.
I feel it's my duty under your command

802
01:11:49,974 --> 01:11:54,228
to suggest that we wait
until it gets up to 1,000, sir.

803
01:11:55,938 --> 01:11:58,440
What if we don't live that long?

804
01:12:01,610 --> 01:12:04,697
- 500?
- 500 would be good, yeah.

805
01:12:04,780 --> 01:12:06,740
- Yes, sir.
- Yeah.

806
01:12:09,368 --> 01:12:12,121
- Get some sleep, Corporal.
- Yes, sir.

807
01:13:18,687 --> 01:13:20,940
«Who's got sulfa powder?»

808
01:13:23,317 --> 01:13:27,446
«Medic! My buddy's bleeding!
He needs a tourniquet!»

809
01:13:27,529 --> 01:13:29,073
- Wade.
«- Yes, sir?»

810
01:13:29,156 --> 01:13:31,116
- See what you can do.
«- Yes, sir.»

811
01:13:31,200 --> 01:13:34,536
Hold on, fellas.
It won't be much longer.

812
01:13:34,703 --> 01:13:36,538
How we doing here?

813
01:13:37,206 --> 01:13:38,499
All right.

814
01:13:38,582 --> 01:13:41,126
Yeah, doing all right.
Don't worry about it.

815
01:13:41,210 --> 01:13:42,962
Doc's in town.

816
01:13:43,379 --> 01:13:44,727
It's all right. It's all right.

817
01:13:44,827 --> 01:13:46,090
Don't worry, fellas.

818
01:13:46,173 --> 01:13:48,717
The 29th Infantry's breaking through,
they'll be here soon.

819
01:13:48,801 --> 01:13:51,136
«Plasma. Anybody got plasma?»

820
01:13:51,220 --> 01:13:55,099
- Captain. Hey, Captain.
- Soldier, you want to fill me in?

821
01:13:55,182 --> 01:13:57,142
«Yeah. Lieutenant DeWindt, sir.»

822
01:13:57,226 --> 01:14:00,854
99th Troop Carrier Squadron,
carrying in 327th Glider Infantry.

823
01:14:00,938 --> 01:14:02,481
This one was mine, sir.

824
01:14:02,564 --> 01:14:03,983
- I was the pilot.
- Private?

825
01:14:04,066 --> 01:14:05,909
- Twenty-two men dead.
- Private, take care of...

826
01:14:05,920 --> 01:14:08,756
I ended up over there without a scratch.
It took my co-pilot's head right off.

827
01:14:08,770 --> 01:14:10,397
Well, where's the unit?
Who are these people?

828
01:14:10,405 --> 01:14:13,408
Well, the guys we came in with, sir,
they headed off first night.

829
01:14:13,409 --> 01:14:14,702
Haven't seen them since.

830
01:14:14,785 --> 01:14:18,831
Meantime, other guys keep showing up,
one, two, half-dozen at a time.

831
01:14:18,914 --> 01:14:21,709
Then some officer'll come along
and patch together a mixed unit,

832
01:14:21,720 --> 01:14:24,320
- head off to make trouble, sir.
- Water. I need a canteen over here.

833
01:14:24,336 --> 01:14:26,338
We're looking for a Private James Ryan.

834
01:14:26,422 --> 01:14:28,674
He's in Baker Company,
the 506 of the 101st.

835
01:14:28,757 --> 01:14:31,279
No, you got me, sir.
A lot of guys come in and out of here.

836
01:14:31,379 --> 01:14:32,636
- Upham.
«- Yes, sir.»

837
01:14:32,720 --> 01:14:34,555
Check out that squad.
See if Ryan's in it.

838
01:14:34,638 --> 01:14:36,306
Yes, sir.

839
01:14:37,683 --> 01:14:39,101
Reiben.

840
01:14:39,601 --> 01:14:43,689
Smell that leg right there.
Find out if it's south of cheese.

841
01:14:49,319 --> 01:14:50,654
What?

842
01:14:52,110 --> 01:14:54,110
<Juden!>

843
01:14:55,530 --> 01:14:56,337
<Juden!>

844
01:14:56,340 --> 01:14:57,516
«Keep moving.»

845
01:14:57,578 --> 01:14:59,455
«Keep moving!»

846
01:15:00,372 --> 01:15:02,750
I'm <Juden>, you know?

847
01:15:04,960 --> 01:15:07,546
Yeah, I couldn't pry him out of there,
hard as I tried.

848
01:15:07,629 --> 01:15:09,882
- I'd need a winch.
- Yeah.

849
01:15:14,011 --> 01:15:15,304
Stars.

850
01:15:15,679 --> 01:15:20,225
Yep, Brigadier General Amend,
Deputy Commander, 101st.

851
01:15:21,060 --> 01:15:23,604
Some fucking genius had the great idea

852
01:15:23,687 --> 01:15:25,230
of welding a couple of steel plates

853
01:15:25,314 --> 01:15:28,567
onto our deck to keep
the general safe from ground fire.

854
01:15:28,650 --> 01:15:30,607
Unfortunately,
they forgot to tell me about it

855
01:15:30,707 --> 01:15:32,738
«until we were just getting airborne.»

856
01:15:32,821 --> 01:15:35,824
«Well, that's like trying
to fly a freight train. Okay.»

857
01:15:36,492 --> 01:15:39,870
Gross overload.
Trim characteristics all shot to hell.

858
01:15:40,245 --> 01:15:43,248
I nearly broke both my arms
trying to keep her level.

859
01:15:43,332 --> 01:15:45,459
And when we released,

860
01:15:45,542 --> 01:15:47,836
you know, I cut as hard as I could,

861
01:15:47,920 --> 01:15:51,423
tried to gain some altitude
and still keep her from stalling.

862
01:15:51,507 --> 01:15:55,677
We came down like a fucking meteor.
And this is how we ended up.

863
01:15:57,846 --> 01:16:01,100
And the others, they stopped easy
enough okay though, you know?

864
01:16:01,183 --> 01:16:04,978
We were just... We were just
too damn heavy, you know?

865
01:16:05,062 --> 01:16:06,855
The grass was wet.

866
01:16:07,689 --> 01:16:09,858
Downward slope and all.

867
01:16:10,567 --> 01:16:12,486
Twenty-two guys dead.

868
01:16:15,280 --> 01:16:18,784
- All that for a general?
- One man.

869
01:16:21,036 --> 01:16:24,331
- A lot of that going around.
- <Fubar>.

870
01:16:24,915 --> 01:16:26,875
- <Fubar>.
- <Fubar>.

871
01:16:27,668 --> 01:16:29,086
<Fubar>.

872
01:16:29,169 --> 01:16:31,296
You all got that right.

873
01:16:31,497 --> 01:16:33,715
Hey, I looked up "<Fubar>"
in the German dictionary.

874
01:16:33,799 --> 01:16:35,017
There's no "<Fubar>" in there.

875
01:16:35,117 --> 01:16:36,135
«- Upham.»
- Yes, sir?

876
01:16:36,218 --> 01:16:39,088
There's more paratroops out there.
Find out if one of them is Ryan.

877
01:16:39,188 --> 01:16:40,305
«Yes, sir.»

878
01:16:40,389 --> 01:16:43,100
Oh, you might want
to check these out, sir.

879
01:16:43,183 --> 01:16:44,726
Dog tags.

880
01:16:44,810 --> 01:16:47,729
«More than I really want to count, sir.»

881
01:16:48,939 --> 01:16:51,775
I've covered a lot of bodies, sir.

882
01:16:51,900 --> 01:16:53,318
«Jackson.»

883
01:16:53,944 --> 01:16:56,780
«- Start going through those.»
- Yes, sir.

884
01:16:58,031 --> 01:16:59,575
I'll help.

885
01:17:01,827 --> 01:17:03,078
What do you think, Jackson?

886
01:17:03,162 --> 01:17:04,371
Do you think
that little prick's in there?

887
01:17:04,454 --> 01:17:07,457
Well, if he is, I'm gonna find him.
I bet that son of a bitch is here.

888
01:17:07,541 --> 01:17:09,498
I got big money saying
this guy's still alive.

889
01:17:09,598 --> 01:17:11,670
10 bucks says I nail him first.

890
01:17:11,753 --> 01:17:14,493
- Let's see who we got in here.
- You mugs don't stand a chance.

891
01:17:14,577 --> 01:17:16,495
All right, you think this little
shit bird is in here or what?

892
01:17:16,579 --> 01:17:18,093
Just keep looking.

893
01:17:18,594 --> 01:17:20,762
All right. Gary Lanico.

894
01:17:20,846 --> 01:17:22,639
Ben Rubino. Mike Cessacchio.

895
01:17:22,723 --> 01:17:24,593
I swear.
All the guineas are buying it, huh?

896
01:17:24,693 --> 01:17:26,351
«Oh, come on, not the right name.»

897
01:17:26,435 --> 01:17:29,479
«Wee Willie Winkie,
that's a buddy of yours.»

898
01:17:29,730 --> 01:17:32,107
«We gotta find this prick.»

899
01:17:36,445 --> 01:17:38,280
Where is this son of a bitch?

900
01:17:38,363 --> 01:17:41,537
Don't mix them up, Jackson, all right?
Keep them in your own fucking pile.

901
01:17:41,637 --> 01:17:43,327
How am I supposed to know
who we got?

902
01:17:43,410 --> 01:17:46,079
Why don't you just shut up,
Reiben? All right.

903
01:17:46,163 --> 01:17:49,666
- Everybody be friends.
- Cranky there, huh?

904
01:17:50,792 --> 01:17:53,587
- I think I got a winner.
- What you talking about?

905
01:17:53,670 --> 01:17:55,130
Ryan.

906
01:17:55,339 --> 01:17:57,925
- Ryan.
- Take a look at that, Mellish.

907
01:17:58,467 --> 01:18:00,467
You know what?
You're a genius. You really are.

908
01:18:00,567 --> 01:18:01,678
R-I-E-N-N-E.

909
01:18:01,762 --> 01:18:03,722
«That's Rienne and that's French.
All right.»

910
01:18:03,805 --> 01:18:05,891
«- You know what that means?
- It means nothing.»

911
01:18:05,974 --> 01:18:08,018
«- What beats three of a kind?
- I got shit here.»

912
01:18:08,118 --> 01:18:11,730
«- I got all guys from New York.
- I got a full house.»

913
01:18:11,813 --> 01:18:14,074
«- Do you need a hand with that?
- I got a full house.»

914
01:18:14,174 --> 01:18:15,275
I got you beat.

915
01:18:15,359 --> 01:18:17,533
- I got the straight flush.
- Full house, he's got.

916
01:18:17,633 --> 01:18:20,072
«You were looking at my tags.
You're cheating, you know?»

917
01:18:20,155 --> 01:18:22,241
«- Ryan.
- Fucking unreal, this guy.»

918
01:18:22,324 --> 01:18:24,910
«Do you need a hand with that?
Can you read that shit?»

919
01:18:24,993 --> 01:18:27,579
Jesus Christ. Look at this poor bastard.

920
01:18:27,663 --> 01:18:30,791
«- I guess they're not bullet-proof, huh?
- Guess not. All right?»

921
01:18:30,874 --> 01:18:32,744
«I don't like
what he's got between his ears.»

922
01:18:32,844 --> 01:18:35,254
«Sort of like what you fellas got
between your legs.»

923
01:18:35,337 --> 01:18:37,422
«- We got to give him that.
- That's not bad.»

924
01:18:37,506 --> 01:18:39,007
«Not bad with you, Jackson.»

925
01:18:39,132 --> 01:18:41,093
All right, I got three of a kind.
All right.

926
01:18:41,176 --> 01:18:43,046
- Full house.
- What the hell are you doing?

927
01:18:43,146 --> 01:18:44,930
The whole goddamn
Airborne's watching.

928
01:18:45,013 --> 01:18:46,515
These aren't poker chips.

929
01:18:46,598 --> 01:18:50,435
«- All right, all right, all right.
- Put them back in there!»

930
01:19:13,959 --> 01:19:15,627
He's not here.

931
01:19:20,048 --> 01:19:22,467
Maybe we should bust up
into a couple of different groups, huh?

932
01:19:22,551 --> 01:19:23,802
And wander the woods
like Hansel and Gretel,

933
01:19:23,885 --> 01:19:24,970
calling his name.

934
01:19:25,053 --> 01:19:28,223
He's bound to hear us sooner
or later. Ryan!

935
01:19:28,307 --> 01:19:31,476
That might be
a little hard to do, Captain.

936
01:19:32,185 --> 01:19:35,439
Maybe the locals have seen him.
Hey, you know...

937
01:19:38,734 --> 01:19:41,278
Ryan! Anybody know Ryan,
101st Airborne?

938
01:19:41,361 --> 01:19:45,157
Ryan? You know a guy named Ryan?
Private James Ryan from Iowa?

939
01:19:45,240 --> 01:19:47,284
Anybody know a Ryan?

940
01:19:47,743 --> 01:19:49,703
James Ryan!

941
01:19:49,786 --> 01:19:55,751
Hey, Joe, doesn't Mandelsohn pal
around with a Ryan from C Company?

942
01:19:55,834 --> 01:19:59,129
- Yeah. I think so.
- Bring him up here, would you?

943
01:20:08,233 --> 01:20:11,016
- Do you know Private Ryan?
- You're gonna have to speak up, sir.

944
01:20:11,099 --> 01:20:12,309
You're gonna have to speak up, sir.

945
01:20:12,392 --> 01:20:14,061
- My hearing is not good!
- It comes and goes!

946
01:20:14,144 --> 01:20:15,354
- It comes and goes!
- A German grenade went off

947
01:20:15,437 --> 01:20:17,872
- next to his ear.
- A grenade went off right by my head!

948
01:20:17,972 --> 01:20:20,400
Got it, got it.
Do you know Private Ryan?

949
01:20:20,484 --> 01:20:21,943
Who?

950
01:20:22,027 --> 01:20:24,488
Private Ryan! James Ryan!

951
01:20:24,571 --> 01:20:28,784
- Jimmy Ryan?
- James! James Francis Ryan!

952
01:20:28,867 --> 01:20:32,704
- No, no, no. James Francis Ryan.
- All right. Get me a pencil.

953
01:20:32,788 --> 01:20:35,123
Something to write on.
Something to write on.

954
01:20:35,207 --> 01:20:37,709
Quick! Quick! Come on, a pencil!

955
01:20:39,461 --> 01:20:41,254
A small one, sir.

956
01:20:41,880 --> 01:20:43,006
Write this down.

957
01:20:43,090 --> 01:20:45,050
James Francis Ryan, question mark.

958
01:20:45,133 --> 01:20:46,927
Iowa, question mark.

959
01:20:47,010 --> 01:20:49,513
Do you know him? Does he know him?

960
01:20:49,596 --> 01:20:51,640
Read the message. Look.

961
01:20:53,475 --> 01:20:57,521
- Yeah. Of course I know him, sir.
- Does he know where he is?

