What is it, $300? Is that it? 300?
I'm a schoolteacher.

1194
01:40:06,585 --> 01:40:08,796
I teach English composition

1195
01:40:10,130 --> 01:40:12,299
in this little town called
Addley, Pennsylvania.

1196
01:40:12,424 --> 01:40:14,176
The last 11 years,

1197
01:40:14,969 --> 01:40:18,013
I've been at
Thomas Alva Edison High School.

1198
01:40:19,932 --> 01:40:23,602
I was the coach of the baseball team
in the springtime.

1199
01:40:26,146 --> 01:40:27,815
I'll be doggone.

1200
01:40:28,482 --> 01:40:31,735
Back home, when I'd tell people
what I do for a living,

1201
01:40:31,819 --> 01:40:34,780
they'd think, "Well, that figures."

1202
01:40:36,657 --> 01:40:38,867
But over here, it's a...

1203
01:40:40,494 --> 01:40:42,162
A big...

1204
01:40:43,414 --> 01:40:45,082
A big mystery.

1205
01:40:46,125 --> 01:40:48,836
So I guess I've changed some.

1206
01:40:51,505 --> 01:40:54,675
Sometimes I wonder
if I've changed so much

1207
01:40:54,800 --> 01:40:59,346
my wife is even going to recognize me
whenever it is I get back to her.

1208
01:41:00,848 --> 01:41:03,434
And how I'll ever be able to...

1209
01:41:05,978 --> 01:41:08,606
To tell her about days like today.

1210
01:41:11,859 --> 01:41:13,193
Ryan...

1211
01:41:14,320 --> 01:41:17,489
I don't know anything about Ryan.
I don't care.

1212
01:41:18,157 --> 01:41:21,827
The man means nothing to me,
it's just a name. But if...

1213
01:41:23,662 --> 01:41:26,165
You know, if going to Ramelle

1214
01:41:26,269 --> 01:41:27,791
and finding him, so he can go home,

1215
01:41:27,875 --> 01:41:29,962
if that earns me the right
to get back to my wife

1216
01:41:30,062 --> 01:41:34,316
well, then... Then that's my mission.

1217
01:41:35,966 --> 01:41:37,551
You want to leave?

1218
01:41:37,635 --> 01:41:40,679
You want to go off and fight the war?

1219
01:41:43,557 --> 01:41:45,017
All right.

1220
01:41:46,352 --> 01:41:48,896
All right, I won't stop you.

1221
01:41:48,979 --> 01:41:51,565
I'll even put in the paperwork.

1222
01:41:53,525 --> 01:41:57,905
I just know that every man I kill,
the farther away from home I feel.

1223
01:43:23,115 --> 01:43:24,658
~By memories.~

1224
01:43:25,993 --> 01:43:28,078
~Of the days gone by.~

1225
01:43:29,913 --> 01:43:31,665
~In my solitude.~

1226
01:43:32,624 --> 01:43:35,085
~You taunt me.~

1227
01:43:35,169 --> 01:43:38,672
~With memories that never die.~

1228
01:43:39,923 --> 01:43:42,342
~I sit in my chair.~

1229
01:43:42,468 --> 01:43:44,678
~Filled with despair.~

1230
01:43:44,762 --> 01:43:46,597
~There's no one.~

1231
01:43:46,680 --> 01:43:49,099
~Could be so sad.~

1232
01:43:49,975 --> 01:43:52,019
~With gloom everywhere~

1233
01:43:52,102 --> 01:43:54,688
~I sit and I stare...~

1234
01:44:08,619 --> 01:44:10,704
Halftrack! Cover!

1235
01:44:26,386 --> 01:44:29,890
«Who's doing the shooting?
Who's doing the shooting?»

1236
01:44:50,828 --> 01:44:53,437
Get ready to move on their left flank!
Take their left flank!

1237
01:44:53,537 --> 01:44:56,456
Hold on and make sure they're down!

1238
01:45:17,312 --> 01:45:19,940
«101st! We're coming out!»

1239
01:45:27,364 --> 01:45:30,325
That was a recon element, 2nd SS.

1240
01:45:31,660 --> 01:45:35,247
We've been expecting a probe.
That must have been it.

1241
01:45:37,124 --> 01:45:40,544
Captain Miller,
Charlie Company, 2nd Rangers.

1242
01:45:40,627 --> 01:45:42,713
Corporal Henderson,
Easy Company, 501st.

1243
01:45:42,796 --> 01:45:44,298
Ryan. First of the 506th.

1244
01:45:44,381 --> 01:45:46,758
PFC Toynbe, Third of the 506th.

1245
01:45:46,842 --> 01:45:48,802
James Francis Ryan?

1246
01:45:48,886 --> 01:45:51,388
Yes, sir. How'd you guess that?

1247
01:46:03,150 --> 01:46:06,111
Looks like you guys got hit pretty hard.

1248
01:46:06,194 --> 01:46:09,740
Yes, sir. Small unit action.

1249
01:46:12,159 --> 01:46:15,746
They came in,
and beat the hell out of us with 88s.

1250
01:46:21,960 --> 01:46:23,700
Tell you what, sir,
if you're our relief,

1251
01:46:23,800 --> 01:46:25,505
I'm gonna file a complaint.

1252
01:46:25,589 --> 01:46:27,549
I wouldn't blame you.

1253
01:46:28,300 --> 01:46:30,052
Who's your CO?

1254
01:46:31,637 --> 01:46:34,431
It would have been
Captain Jennings, sir.

1255
01:46:34,514 --> 01:46:38,977
I'm afraid the best we can muster up
right now is a corporal.

1256
01:46:39,061 --> 01:46:41,605
So, what are you guys all about?

1257
01:46:42,189 --> 01:46:44,691
We're here for him. Ryan.

1258
01:46:46,026 --> 01:46:47,486
Me, sir?

1259
01:46:56,828 --> 01:46:59,206
James Francis Ryan of Iowa?

1260
01:47:00,040 --> 01:47:03,460
Yes, sir.
Payton, Iowa, that's correct, but...

1261
01:47:03,543 --> 01:47:05,545
What is this about?

1262
01:47:07,381 --> 01:47:10,217
Your brothers were killed in combat.

1263
01:47:17,015 --> 01:47:18,642
Which ones?

1264
01:47:21,561 --> 01:47:23,063
All of them.

1265
01:47:32,906 --> 01:47:34,533
On the level?

1266
01:47:35,909 --> 01:47:37,911
Yeah. I'm afraid so.

1267
01:47:40,664 --> 01:47:42,582
You might want to take
some time with this.

1268
01:47:42,708 --> 01:47:45,752
If there's someplace
you want to go and...

1269
01:47:54,761 --> 01:47:57,681
- What's this all about?
- Ryan lost his brothers.

1270
01:47:57,764 --> 01:48:00,100
- Which one?
- All of them.

1271
01:48:05,105 --> 01:48:06,440
You...

1272
01:48:09,109 --> 01:48:12,404
You came all the way
out here to tell me that?

1273
01:48:14,114 --> 01:48:16,283
Well, you're going home.

1274
01:48:17,784 --> 01:48:20,370
Our orders are to bring you back.

1275
01:48:23,623 --> 01:48:25,292
Bring me back?

1276
01:48:27,627 --> 01:48:31,131
Corporal Henderson, I don't mean
to leave you even more shorthanded,

1277
01:48:31,256 --> 01:48:32,591
but orders are orders.

1278
01:48:32,674 --> 01:48:35,510
Any communication about when
you're going to be relieved up here?

1279
01:48:35,635 --> 01:48:36,870
Sir, there's no way to tell. I mean,

1280
01:48:36,970 --> 01:48:38,497
we have no idea
what's happening south of us.

1281
01:48:38,597 --> 01:48:39,931
I have my orders, too, sir.

1282
01:48:40,015 --> 01:48:41,892
They don't include me
abandoning my post.

1283
01:48:41,975 --> 01:48:44,895
I understand that,
but this changes things.

1284
01:48:44,978 --> 01:48:47,355
I don't see that it does, sir.

1285
01:48:48,982 --> 01:48:51,985
The Chief of Staff
for the United States Army says it does.

1286
01:48:52,110 --> 01:48:54,946
Sir, our orders are to hold
this bridge at all cost.

1287
01:48:55,030 --> 01:48:57,532
Now, our planes in the 82nd
have taken out every bridge

1288
01:48:57,657 --> 01:48:59,618
across the Merderet
with the exception of two.

1289
01:48:59,701 --> 01:49:01,286
One at Valognes and this one here.

1290
01:49:01,369 --> 01:49:02,630
We let the Germans take them,

1291
01:49:02,713 --> 01:49:04,887
we're gonna lose our foothold
and have to displace.

1292
01:49:04,987 --> 01:49:07,834
Private, your outfit wants to stay,
that's one thing.

1293
01:49:07,959 --> 01:49:09,133
But your party's over here.

1294
01:49:09,253 --> 01:49:11,427
Sir, I can't leave
until at least reinforcements...

1295
01:49:11,510 --> 01:49:13,799
You got three minutes
to gather your gear.

1296
01:49:13,882 --> 01:49:16,491
Sir, what about them?
I mean, there's barely hardly enough...

1297
01:49:16,591 --> 01:49:18,092
Hey, asshole!

1298
01:49:18,303 --> 01:49:22,182
Two of our guys already died
trying to find you, all right?

1299
01:49:27,187 --> 01:49:29,898
- Sir?
- That's right.

1300
01:49:39,783 --> 01:49:44,287
- What were their names?
- Irwin Wade and Adrian Caparzo.

1301
01:49:46,248 --> 01:49:47,791
Wade and...

1302
01:49:49,292 --> 01:49:50,710
Caparzo.

1303
01:50:03,140 --> 01:50:05,559
It doesn't make any sense.

1304
01:50:07,644 --> 01:50:11,898
It doesn't make sense, sir.
Why? Why do I deserve to go?

1305
01:50:11,982 --> 01:50:16,153
Why not any of these guys?
They all fought just as hard as me!

1306
01:50:19,781 --> 01:50:22,868
Is that what they're
supposed to tell your mother

1307
01:50:22,951 --> 01:50:26,288
when they send her another
folded American flag?

1308
01:50:33,503 --> 01:50:35,922
Tell her that when you found me,

1309
01:50:36,006 --> 01:50:39,676
I was here and I was
with the only brothers that I have left,

1310
01:50:39,759 --> 01:50:43,013
and that there's no way
I was gonna desert them.

1311
01:50:44,181 --> 01:50:46,349
I think she'll understand that.

1312
01:50:46,433 --> 01:50:49,436
There's no way I'm leaving this bridge.

1313
01:51:32,437 --> 01:51:34,481
What are your orders?

1314
01:51:36,316 --> 01:51:39,694
Sergeant, we have crossed
some strange boundary here.

1315
01:51:40,654 --> 01:51:43,281
The world has taken a turn
for the surreal.

1316
01:51:43,365 --> 01:51:46,201
Clearly, but the question still stands.

1317
01:51:46,868 --> 01:51:49,829
I don't know. What do you think?

1318
01:51:50,914 --> 01:51:53,708
«You don't want to know what I think.»

1319
01:51:55,585 --> 01:51:57,254
No, Mike, I do.

1320
01:51:58,964 --> 01:52:02,259
Well, part of me thinks the kid's right.

1321
01:52:02,342 --> 01:52:04,886
What's he done to deserve this?

1322
01:52:04,970 --> 01:52:08,932
He wants to stay here, fine,
let's leave him and go home.

1323
01:52:10,183 --> 01:52:11,476
Yeah.

1324
01:52:12,018 --> 01:52:17,148
But another part of me thinks
what if, by some miracle, we stay

1325
01:52:17,232 --> 01:52:19,859
and actually make it out of here?

1326
01:52:20,777 --> 01:52:24,406
Someday we might look back on this
and decide that

1327
01:52:24,489 --> 01:52:27,909
saving Private Ryan
was the one decent thing

1328
01:52:27,993 --> 01:52:30,912
we were able to pull out of this whole.

1329
01:52:30,996 --> 01:52:33,123
God-awful, shitty mess.

1330
01:52:34,791 --> 01:52:37,294
That's what I was thinking, sir.

1331
01:52:38,461 --> 01:52:40,630
Like you said, Captain,

1332
01:52:42,424 --> 01:52:44,134
we do that,

1333
01:52:44,592 --> 01:52:47,387
we all earn the right to go home.

1334
01:52:50,265 --> 01:52:51,808
Oh, brother.

1335
01:52:55,270 --> 01:52:57,564
This is everything.

1336
01:52:58,315 --> 01:53:03,945
You got the two 30-caliber machine
guns, 17 grenades, 11 Hawkins mines.

1337
01:53:04,696 --> 01:53:08,033
You got the two bazookas,
but they only got eight rounds left,

1338
01:53:08,116 --> 01:53:10,327
and assorted small arms.

1339
01:53:10,410 --> 01:53:13,913
We had a 60 mortar
but an arty round took it out.

1340
01:53:13,997 --> 01:53:16,666
Might as well be spit wads
if they roll on us with tanks.

1341
01:53:16,750 --> 01:53:20,003
- Which they're sure to do.
- What are you thinking, sir?

1342
01:53:20,086 --> 01:53:24,716
Well, I'm thinking they're going to try
to whip around the flanks.

1343
01:53:29,262 --> 01:53:31,556
Unless we can draw
them up this main road here

1344
01:53:31,639 --> 01:53:32,770
in between these buildings

1345
01:53:32,870 --> 01:53:36,811
where all the rubble makes
a bit of a bottleneck.

1346
01:53:36,895 --> 01:53:38,938
- Disable 'em?
- If we can.

1347
01:53:39,022 --> 01:53:40,607
Make that tank a 60-ton roadblock.

1348
01:53:40,690 --> 01:53:42,525
We do that, we got
a fighting chance at their flanks.

1349
01:53:42,609 --> 01:53:45,028
Yes, sir that's good. Split them up.
Don't let them mass anywhere.

1350
01:53:45,111 --> 01:53:48,073
Hit them hard as we can, one-on-one,
and fall back to the bridge.

1351
01:53:48,156 --> 01:53:50,367
Machine gun on the move down here,
and number two up high somewhere

1352
01:53:50,450 --> 01:53:52,494
to piss a little bad news down
on their heads.

1353
01:53:52,577 --> 01:53:54,788
That would be the idea.

1354
01:53:55,372 --> 01:53:56,831
Jackson.

1355
01:53:57,457 --> 01:53:59,751
If we can, I'd like to get you up
in that bell tower.

1356
01:53:59,834 --> 01:54:00,835
Yes, sir.

1357
01:54:00,919 --> 01:54:02,879
Give you a little company
if you need it.

1358
01:54:02,962 --> 01:54:05,006
Yes, sir. Some company couldn't hurt.

1359
01:54:05,090 --> 01:54:09,135
I'd say a.30 with about
1,000 rounds would be okay.

1360
01:54:09,219 --> 01:54:11,262
Parker, job opportunity.

1361
01:54:11,346 --> 01:54:13,348
Yeah. Well, it's not the worst idea
ever, Captain.

1362
01:54:13,431 --> 01:54:15,016
It's just that everything depends
on getting the tank

1363
01:54:15,100 --> 01:54:17,185
down this main road for us
to knock out, right?

1364
01:54:17,310 --> 01:54:20,355
So how the hell do you
plan on doing that?

1365
01:54:20,814 --> 01:54:23,901
Reiben's right. As our esteemed
colleague from the Airborne pointed out,

1366
01:54:24,001 --> 01:54:26,152
what we got here are
a bunch of spit wads,

1367
01:54:26,236 --> 01:54:30,073
so how do we stop the tank
if we get it to commit?

1368
01:54:30,156 --> 01:54:32,575
Give it a rabbit to chase.

1369
01:54:32,659 --> 01:54:35,829
We could hit the tank in the tracks.

1370
01:54:35,912 --> 01:54:37,997
Yeah, but with what?

1371
01:54:39,707 --> 01:54:43,545
- Well, we could try a sticky bomb.
- Sticky bomb, sir?

1372
01:54:44,754 --> 01:54:48,591
- Sir, are you making that up?
- No. It's in the field manual.

1373
01:54:48,675 --> 01:54:50,552
You check it out if you want to.

1374
01:54:50,635 --> 01:54:52,720
We seem to be out of field manuals, sir.

1375
01:54:52,804 --> 01:54:54,722
Perhaps you can enlighten us?

1376
01:54:54,806 --> 01:54:56,806
All right, you have
some demolition, don't you?

1377
01:54:56,906 --> 01:54:58,309
Some TNT or some composition B?

1378
01:54:58,393 --> 01:55:00,103
Yeah, that, sir, is the one thing
we got plenty of.

1379
01:55:00,186 --> 01:55:03,056
I got that bridge wired with enough
composition B to blow it twice.

1380
01:55:03,156 --> 01:55:04,941
All right. You can spare some, then.

1381
01:55:05,024 --> 01:55:08,278
You take a standard-issue GI sock,

1382
01:55:08,361 --> 01:55:11,489
cram it with as much
comp B as it can hold,

1383
01:55:11,573 --> 01:55:14,033
rig up a simple fuse,

1384
01:55:14,117 --> 01:55:16,661
then you coat the whole thing
with axle grease.

1385
01:55:16,744 --> 01:55:18,746
That way, when you throw it,

1386
01:55:18,830 --> 01:55:21,249
it should stick.
It's a bomb that sticks.

1387
01:55:21,332 --> 01:55:22,959
It's a sticky bomb.

1388
01:55:23,042 --> 01:55:25,651
You come up with a better way
to knock the tracks off a tank,

1389
01:55:25,751 --> 01:55:27,172
I'm all ears.

1390
01:55:27,255 --> 01:55:30,800
This is good.
Now we got to surrender our socks.

1391
01:55:45,273 --> 01:55:46,774
Haul away.

1392
01:56:00,788 --> 01:56:02,790
All right, select the field of fire.

1393
01:56:02,874 --> 01:56:04,709
Crossfire with the one
in the bell tower.

1394
01:56:04,792 --> 01:56:08,087
All right, I can cover
12 to nine from here.

1395
01:56:11,341 --> 01:56:13,426
«- Easy!
- I got her!»

1396
01:56:47,794 --> 01:56:49,671
Here are the mines.

1397
01:57:00,598 --> 01:57:03,017
For being the best we can do,

1398
01:57:03,101 --> 01:57:07,105
that forward machine gun
is not in a terrible firing position.

1399
01:57:09,774 --> 01:57:12,277
And this position right here,

1400
01:57:14,320 --> 01:57:15,947
this is the Alamo.

1401
01:57:16,531 --> 01:57:20,201
They push us back this far,
last man alive blows the bridge.

1402
01:57:20,285 --> 01:57:22,328
We only got a 30-second delay
on that fuse,

1403
01:57:22,412 --> 01:57:24,543
so let everyone know that
if you are that last man

1404
01:57:24,643 --> 01:57:28,626
you better hurry your ass off,
or you're not going to be alive long.

1405
01:57:28,710 --> 01:57:32,130
Captain? Where am I during all this?

1406
01:57:33,047 --> 01:57:35,008
Never more than
two feet away from me,

1407
01:57:35,091 --> 01:57:37,302
and that's not negotiable.

1408
01:57:38,428 --> 01:57:40,847
I'll get some ammo. Come on.

1409
01:57:43,891 --> 01:57:45,184
- Hey, Upham.
- Yes.

1410
01:57:45,268 --> 01:57:47,145
- Listen to me, all right?
- Yeah.

1411
01:57:47,228 --> 01:57:48,771
- You're listening?
- Yes.

1412
01:57:48,855 --> 01:57:50,940
All right, we're gonna be displacing

1413
01:57:51,024 --> 01:57:52,894
and falling back like crazy
sons of bitches.

1414
01:57:52,994 --> 01:57:53,818
Right up there.

1415
01:57:53,901 --> 01:57:57,363
So you got to be Johnny on the spot
with the ammo, or we're dead.

1416
01:57:57,447 --> 01:57:59,157
- Right.
- You understand that?

1417
01:57:59,240 --> 01:58:01,534
- Johnny on the spot.
- Yeah.

1418
01:58:01,618 --> 01:58:04,746
- You all right?
- Yeah. Yes.

1419
01:58:05,038 --> 01:58:06,331
You know, when we were
shipping out of England

1420
01:58:06,414 --> 01:58:08,893
the supply sergeant was handing
out cartons of cigarettes,

1421
01:58:08,993 --> 01:58:12,079
and I said "No, thank you,
I don't smoke."

1422
01:58:12,545 --> 01:58:14,172
"I don't smoke."

1423
01:58:16,007 --> 01:58:18,968
- Quite a situation, huh?
- Unbelievable.

1424
01:58:20,303 --> 01:58:25,850
Here. Fucked up beyond
all recognition, right?

1425
01:58:26,309 --> 01:58:28,186
You got that right.

1426
01:58:30,438 --> 01:58:31,814
<Fubar>.

1427
01:58:34,150 --> 01:58:35,193
Ouch.

1428
01:58:35,485 --> 01:58:37,111
- Yeah, well...
- <Fubar>.

1429
01:58:37,195 --> 01:58:39,697
It's going to be a real show, huh?

1430
01:58:39,781 --> 01:58:41,699
Yeah. Okay.

1431
01:58:47,914 --> 01:58:49,582
Take it easy.

1432
01:58:50,750 --> 01:58:52,251
<Fubar>.

1433
01:59:30,123 --> 01:59:34,502
«- Who's that singing, sir?»
- Edith Piaf.

1434
01:59:36,921 --> 01:59:39,465
«What's she so upset about?»

