1472
02:01:39,502 --> 02:01:41,155
- Double E?
- These things are massive.

1473
02:01:41,255 --> 02:01:42,463
Those are big.

1474
02:01:42,588 --> 02:01:45,925
No. And I've got her convinced
that she's, like, a 42 D, all right?

1475
02:01:46,008 --> 02:01:48,313
So we're in the dressing room,
she's trying to squeeze

1476
02:01:48,413 --> 02:01:51,264
into this side-cut,
silk-ribboned, triple-panel girdle

1477
02:01:51,430 --> 02:01:53,599
with the shelf-lift brassiere.

1478
02:01:53,683 --> 02:01:56,269
And it's beautiful 'cause she's just
pouring out of this thing, you know?

1479
02:01:56,352 --> 02:01:58,104
- Is it really tight?
- No, no. It's beautiful.

1480
02:01:58,187 --> 02:01:59,647
And she sees me, and she can tell

1481
02:01:59,749 --> 02:02:02,358
I got a hard-on the size
of the Statue of Liberty, all right?

1482
02:02:02,441 --> 02:02:04,485
And she says to me,
"Richard, calm down."

1483
02:02:04,610 --> 02:02:07,071
And she says, "When you're over there",

1484
02:02:07,154 --> 02:02:09,031
"if you see anything that upsets you,"

1485
02:02:09,115 --> 02:02:12,201
"or if you're ever scared,
I want you to close your eyes"

1486
02:02:12,285 --> 02:02:15,329
"and think of these. You understand?"

1487
02:02:16,789 --> 02:02:18,958
So I said, "Yes, ma'am."

1488
02:02:32,138 --> 02:02:34,140
«Are you all right, sir?»

1489
02:02:35,182 --> 02:02:37,977
Yeah, I'm just keeping the rhythm.

1490
02:02:42,857 --> 02:02:45,818
«Is it true you were
a teacher back home?»

1491
02:02:46,861 --> 02:02:48,321
Yes.

1492
02:02:48,404 --> 02:02:50,740
See, that's something I could never do,
you know.

1493
02:02:50,823 --> 02:02:55,328
Not after the way me and my brothers
treated our teachers. No, sir.

1494
02:02:57,663 --> 02:03:00,082
I had 1,000 kids like you.

1495
02:03:06,339 --> 02:03:09,008
I can't see my brothers' faces.

1496
02:03:10,343 --> 02:03:13,054
I've been trying,
and I can't see their faces at all.

1497
02:03:13,179 --> 02:03:15,348
Has that ever happened to you?

1498
02:03:15,431 --> 02:03:17,850
You gotta think of a context.

1499
02:03:20,019 --> 02:03:22,146
What does that mean?

1500
02:03:22,229 --> 02:03:24,143
Well, you don't just think
about their faces.

1501
02:03:24,243 --> 02:03:28,914
You think about something specific,
something you've done together.

1502
02:03:32,239 --> 02:03:35,201
Well, when I think of home,
I think of something specific.

1503
02:03:35,284 --> 02:03:38,371
I think of my hammock in the backyard,

1504
02:03:39,205 --> 02:03:43,542
or my wife pruning the rose bushes
in a pair of my old work gloves.

1505
02:03:47,880 --> 02:03:51,175
This one night, two of my brothers came

1506
02:03:51,258 --> 02:03:54,261
and woke me up in
the middle of the night,

1507
02:03:55,096 --> 02:03:58,140
and they said
they had a surprise for me.

1508
02:03:58,724 --> 02:04:01,852
So they took me to the barn,
up into the loft,

1509
02:04:01,936 --> 02:04:04,897
and there was my oldest brother Dan

1510
02:04:06,065 --> 02:04:09,110
with Alice. Alice Jardine.

1511
02:04:12,071 --> 02:04:16,283
I mean, picture a girl who just took
a nosedive from the ugly tree

1512
02:04:16,409 --> 02:04:18,995
and hit every branch coming down.

1513
02:04:20,913 --> 02:04:23,582
And Dan's got her shirt off.

1514
02:04:23,666 --> 02:04:26,460
So he's working on this bra
and he's trying to get it off

1515
02:04:26,585 --> 02:04:29,755
and all of a sudden,
Sean just screams out,

1516
02:04:30,589 --> 02:04:33,968
"Danny, you're a young man!
Don't do it!"

1517
02:04:36,595 --> 02:04:40,141
And so Alice Jardine hears this
and she screams, and she jumps up,

1518
02:04:40,266 --> 02:04:42,180
and she tries to get
running out of the barn,

1519
02:04:42,264 --> 02:04:44,178
but she's still got this shirt
over her head.

1520
02:04:44,278 --> 02:04:47,481
She goes running right into the wall
and knocks herself out.

1521
02:04:47,606 --> 02:04:51,777
So now Dan is just so mad at us,
he starts coming after us,

1522
02:04:51,861 --> 02:04:54,238
but at the same time,
Alice is over there unconscious.

1523
02:04:54,321 --> 02:04:55,823
He's got to wake her up.

1524
02:04:55,948 --> 02:04:59,201
So he grabs her by a leg
and he's dragging her.

1525
02:04:59,285 --> 02:05:02,496
At the same time, he picks up a shovel
and he's going after Sean.

1526
02:05:02,618 --> 02:05:04,792
And Sean said,
"What are you trying to hit me for?"

1527
02:05:04,892 --> 02:05:07,019
"I just did you a favor."

1528
02:05:08,794 --> 02:05:10,671
And so this makes Dan more angry.

1529
02:05:10,796 --> 02:05:13,716
He tries to swing this thing.
He loses the shovel.

1530
02:05:13,799 --> 02:05:16,510
It goes out of his grasp
and hits a kerosene lantern.

1531
02:05:16,635 --> 02:05:19,221
The thing explodes,
the whole barn almost goes up

1532
02:05:19,305 --> 02:05:21,474
because of this thing.

1533
02:05:36,322 --> 02:05:38,240
That was it. That was the last...
That was...

1534
02:05:38,324 --> 02:05:39,909
Dan went off to basic next day.

1535
02:05:39,992 --> 02:05:43,621
That was the last night
the four of us were together.

1536
02:05:43,704 --> 02:05:45,831
That was two years ago.

1537
02:05:47,708 --> 02:05:49,085
Oh, my.

1538
02:05:51,045 --> 02:05:54,590
Tell me about your wife
and those rose bushes.

1539
02:05:55,841 --> 02:05:57,176
No.

1540
02:05:58,385 --> 02:06:01,097
No. That one I save just for me.

1541
